&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
In this way, the fight against climate change is no longer at the heart of Florida's attentions and actions, a move that puts the reality of rising sea level, temperatures, serious floods, toxic algae and tragic weather events that have hit so many places in the world, including the American state. After its entry into force on 1 July, in addition to prohibiting offshore wind turbines, the measure will favour the expansion of natural gas. All at a time when southern Florida is facing a hot wave above average. The legislation removes most references to climate change in state law and reverses much of the policy introduced during the administration of former governor Charlie Crist, a Democrat (2007-2011), reported Axios. The most critical voices have emphasized how this policy move ignores the threat of the 'dead' climate in Florida>, which is second only in Hawaii in the recording of the average annual temperatures. Last summer the so-called "Sun State" recorded a record heat wave, with temperatures that briefly exceeded 37.8 centigrade degrees in southern waters.
&nbsp;
The White House press officer, Karine Jean-Pierre, called the "most shameful" move and warned that there is "very work to do" to mitigate the worst effects of the 'climate change'. "Climate change is an indisputable fact, not an argument open to debate," added Frederica Wilson, member of the Florida delegation to the United States Congress, on X. "The terrible consequences of the climate crisis are evident every day in Florida and attempts to undermine efforts to combat this existential threat are absolutely undesirable and irresponsible." Of the 19.6 million inhabitants of the state, 15 million live in coastal areas, according to the US government's Office for Coastal Management. The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) > denounced the impact of the 2023 heat wave in different locations along the coral reef, 410 kilometers long, which houses marine turtles, breeds, sharks, dolphins and many species of fish. They discovered that less than 22% of the approximately 1,500 coral staghorn - a species that is listed as a candidate for the protection of endangered species - remained alive. Robert Reich, secretary of Bill Clinton's work from 1993 to 1997, stated that this week Florida is facing another wave of hot record.
"Since 1980, 87 climatic and meteorological disasters occurred in Florida with losses of more than $1 billion each," he wrote about X.
&nbsp;
DeSantis has defined the law signed an initiative of "good sense energy policy >" and said that it will keep "oil in our tanks and China outside our state". "We will make sure that foreign opponents like Beijing "have no support in our state," he said. DeSantis suspended his presidential campaign last January and later supported the Republican candidacy of his bitter rival, former President Donald Trump.&nbsp;
