AGI - In a field hospital that became one of the major traumatological centers in Gaza, a doctor who worked in a dozen war zones described the situation as the most "catastrophic" I have ever seen. "It is devastating," said Javed Ali>, head of the International Medical Corps for emergency interventions in Gaza, interviewed by the Afp agency.
The man, speaking from a field hospital to the northwest of the areas of Rafah evacuated from Israel, said that the situation around the city to the far south is "terrible". The hospital, in the coastal area of Al-Mawasi that Israel has designated as "humanitarian zone", has become in a few months in a structure with more than 150 beds, consisting of numerous white tents and containers.
&nbsp;
Since the first orders of evacuation for Rafah were issued on 6 May, in view of a fearful invasion of land of the southernmost part of Gaza, almost half of the 1.4 million people who had taken refuge have left, according to UN agencies. "There was a massive movement of individuals," Ali said, adding that most avoided Al-Mawasi, who was already dramatically overcrowded, instead heading towards the city of Khan Yunis, marked by the war, which was a battlefield until last month.
Those who arrive are "exused, frightened, have no resources>", said Ali, adding that many patients ask "money, support... to be able to transfer their families safely.»
&nbsp;
<div </div
<br Pressure on the field hospital increases from day to day. With limited access to Rafah facilities, the center saw the number of daily visits to its emergency department pass from about 110 to almost 300, said Ali, describing also the presence of "polytrauma cases with broken bones in every part of the body". The situation is even more precipitated after the temporary closure last week of the two main rafts of Rafah, which interrupted the supply of medicines and fuel for the generators of the hospital. Ali said that the field hospital "if he waited for him" and prepared excess stocks, but had not predicted the increase in the number of patients. "The situation is completely out of hand," he said. "Our stocks won't last." He then explained that the structure was already recording shortcomings of "very critical arts". For example, they ended "all pediatric formulations of antibiotics and painkillers" at a time when about 20 children were recovering from surgery. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The biggest concern, however, is the "space", with surgical interventions that doubled compared to the previous average of about 25 per day, said Ali. There has also been a dramatic increase in the workload of the maternity ward, which has passed from about 10 parts per day to about 25, as well as a maximum of eight ceres. With the impossibility for future mothers to access the Rafah maternity hospital, there was also a "massive increase in the number of complicated pregnancy". Ali, who has often worked in war zones in 15 years, from Afghanistan to Sudan, from Nigeria to Ukraine, said that the situation in Gaza is "much more catastrophic". The immense number of trauma cases, lack of resources, interruption of the supply chain...". It's something I've never seen." In most wars, men suffer most gunshot wounds and splinters, but in Gaza the number of injured women and children "is very, very high," Ali said, describing small children "with shattered arts". According to the United Nations, only one third of the 36 existing Gaza hospitals before the war is partially working and displaced persons are often blocked away from health facilities: "Acces has become extremely compromised." The Al-Mawasi Field Hospital became the "main reference center for trauma" in southern Gaza, said Ali, "and we are working in a tent."
